		<id>/index.php/2010/08/automated-monitoring-of-remote-vnc-serve/#comment-3166</id>
		<updated>2010-08-30T20:21:02Z</updated>
		<published>2010-08-30T20:21:02Z</published>
		<content type="html" xml:base="/index.php/webdev/serverprogramming/automated-monitoring-of-remote-vnc-serve/#comment-3166"><![CDATA[<p>I&#8217;ve never had a BSOD but I&#8217;d imagine it&#8217;d stop responding all together and fail at the initial connection attempt.</p>
<p>A simpler solution came to me earlier: since I have access to the webserver I could monitor the access log and flag up a problem if one of the screens hasn&#8217;t accessed anything in a while. </p>
<p>I could even have a javascript/iframe &#8220;pinging&#8221; a specific page every 10 seconds so it&#8217;s easier to check the log and quicker to flag up any problems.</p>
<p>Anyway, still a pretty neat technique which could come in handy for other applications!</p>
]]></content>
